Study: Drivers still distracted, despite tech advances keeping their eyes on the road
Video: A new study by the AAA Foundation for Traffic Safety shows that Siri and other voice activated apps pose a risky distraction for drivers. Researchers spent two years measuring the brain activity of drivers. This week Post transportation reporter, Ashley Halsey III took a ride wearing the organization’s brain scanning device.
By Ashley Halsey III, E-mail the writer
Your eyes may be on the road ahead, but if you’re on the phone or using a voice-activated app to send a text message, there’s a disconnect between your eyeballs and your brain.
“Cognitive distraction is something that drivers aren’t aware of, so they may go through a red light or a stop sign and be totally unaware they’ve missed it,” said David L. Strayer, whose research team at the University of Utah conducted a two-year study of driver behavior. “They will tell you ‘I never saw it,’ because their brain was focused elsewhere.”
(Jonathan Newton/ The Washington Post ) - Russ Martin of AAA, wearing a EEG-configured skull cap, prepares to drive a research vehicle Tuesday while unveiling research demonstrating that new in-car technologies being marketed by automakers can cause dangerous distractions for drivers.
